[{"category":"section","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations","page":"Home","text":"Documentation for BoundaryIntegralEquations.\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations"},{"category":"type","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.AdjointDoubleLayer","page":"Home","text":"AdjointDoubleLayer\n\nFinite-dimensional approximation of the adjoint operator of a double-layer potential integral operator using the Nyström approach.\n\nThis operator maps a density on the boundary of a domain to the potential that it produces.\n\nD^* C^1(Gamma) to C^1(bar Omega) \nD^*u(x) = int_Gamma fracpartialpartial n_xk(x y) varphi(y) dS(y) x in Gamma y in bar Omega\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.AdjointDoubleLayer"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.AdjointDoubleLayer-Tuple{Laplace, BoundaryIntegralEquations.AbstractManifold, AbstractMatrix, AbstractMatrix}","page":"Home","text":"AdjointDoubleLayer(equation::Laplace, source::AbstractManifold, target::AbstractMatrix, target_normals::AbstractMatrix, matrix_factory::Function=default_allocator)\n\nCompute the operator coefficients for source-target interaction\n\nArguments\n\nequation::Laplace: Partial Differential Equation corresponding to this operator\nsource::AbstractManifold: Manifold where the density is defined, i.e. points inside the domain\ntarget::AbstractMatrix: Points where the potential is computed, i.e. points in the boundary of the domain\ntarget_normals::AbstractMatrix: outward unit normal vectors at the target points\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.AdjointDoubleLayer"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.AdjointDoubleLayer-Tuple{Laplace, BoundaryIntegralEquations.AbstractManifold}","page":"Home","text":"AdjointDoubleLayer(equation::Laplace, source::AbstractManifold, matrix_factory::Function=default_allocator)\n\nCompute the operator coefficients for source self interaction\n\nArguments\n\nequation::Laplace: Partial Differential Equation corresponding to this operator\nsource::AbstractManifold: Manifold where the density is defined and where the potential is computed, i.e. boundary of the domain\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.AdjointDoubleLayer"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.DiscreteClosedCurve-Tuple{AbstractMatrix, AbstractMatrix, AbstractMatrix}","page":"Home","text":"DiscreteClosedCurve(x::AbstractMatrix, v::AbstractMatrix, a::AbstractMatrix)\n\ngiven positions, velocities, and accelerations of the curve parametrization, compute the remaining parameters\n\nArguments\n\nx::AbstractMatrix: location of the points\nv::AbstractMatrix: velocity of the curve at each point\na::AbstractMatrix: acceleration of the curve at each point\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.DiscreteClosedCurve"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.DiscreteClosedCurve-Tuple{AbstractMatrix}","page":"Home","text":"DiscreteClosedCurve(x::AbstractMatrix)\n\ngiven positions, compute the velocities and accelerations using periodic spectral differentiation\n\nArguments\n\nx::AbstractMatrix: locations of the points\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.DiscreteClosedCurve"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.DiscreteClosedCurve-Tuple{AbstractVector, Function}","page":"Home","text":"DiscreteClosedCurve(θ::AbstractVector, ρ::Function)\n\nconstruct curve given a list of parameter values and a parametrization\n\nArguments\n\nθ::AbstractVector: list of nodes in parameter space\nρ::Function: function that parametrizes the curve\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.DiscreteClosedCurve"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.DiscreteClosedCurve-Tuple{Int64, Function}","page":"Home","text":"DiscreteClosedCurve(n_points::Int, ρ::Function)\n\nconstruct curve given a number of points and a parametrization using equispaced nodes in parameter space\n\nArguments\n\nn_points::Int: number of nodes\nρ::Function: function that parametrizes the curve\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.DiscreteClosedCurve"},{"category":"type","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.DoubleLayer","page":"Home","text":"DoubleLayer\n\nFinite-dimensional approximation of a double-layer potential integral operator using the Nyström approach.\n\nThis operator maps a density on the boundary of a domain to potential that it produces.\n\nD C^1(Gamma) to C^1(bar Omega)\nDu(x) = int_Gamma fracpartialpartial n_yk(x y) varphi(y) dS(y) x in bar Omega y in Gamma\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.DoubleLayer"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.DoubleLayer-Tuple{Laplace, BoundaryIntegralEquations.AbstractManifold, AbstractMatrix}","page":"Home","text":"DoubleLayer(equation::Laplace, source::AbstractManifold, # source manifold e.g. domain boundary, target::AbstractMatrix, # target points to compute operator, matrix_factory::Function=default_allocator)\n\nCompute the operator coefficients for source-target interaction\n\nArguments\n\nequation::Laplace: Partial Differential Equation corresponding to this operator\nsource::AbstractManifold: Manifold where the density is defined, i.e. boundary of the domain\ntarget::AbstractMatrix: Points where the potential is computed\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.DoubleLayer"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.DoubleLayer-Tuple{Laplace, BoundaryIntegralEquations.AbstractManifold}","page":"Home","text":"DoubleLayer(equation::Laplace, source::AbstractManifold, matrix_factory::Function=default_allocator)\n\nCompute the operator coefficients for source self interaction\n\nArguments\n\nequation::Laplace: Partial Differential Equation corresponding to this operator\nsource::AbstractManifold: Manifold where the density is defined and where the potential is computed, i.e. boundary of the domain\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.DoubleLayer"},{"category":"type","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.Hypersingular","page":"Home","text":"Hypersingular\n\nFinite-dimensional approximation of the hypersingular integral operator using the Nyström approach.\n\nThis operator maps a density on the boundary of a domain to the potential that it produces.\n\nH C^1(Gamma) to C^1(Gamma)\nHu(x) = int_Gammafracpartial^2partial n_x partial n_yk(x y) varphi(y) dS(y) xin Gamma y in Gamma\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.Hypersingular"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.Hypersingular-Tuple{Laplace, BoundaryIntegralEquations.AbstractManifold, HypersingularCorrection}","page":"Home","text":"Hypersingular(equation::Laplace, source::AbstractManifold, correction::HypersingularCorrection, matrix_factory::Function=default_allocator)\n\nCompute the operator coefficients for source self interaction\n\nArguments\n\nequation::Laplace: Partial Differential Equation corresponding to this operator\nsource::AbstractManifold: Manifold where the density is defined and where the potential is computed, i.e. boundary of the domain\ncorrection::HypersingularCorrection: Approach to handle the singularity\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.Hypersingular"},{"category":"type","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.SingleLayer","page":"Home","text":"SingleLayer\n\nFinite-dimensional approximation of a single-layer potential integral operator using the Nyström approach.\n\nThis operator maps a density on the boundary of a domain to the potential that it produces.\n\nS C^1(Gamma) to C^1(bar Omega)\n\nSu(x) = int_Gamma k(x y) varphi(y) dS(y) x in bar Omega y in Gamma\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.SingleLayer"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.SingleLayer-Tuple{Laplace, BoundaryIntegralEquations.AbstractManifold, AbstractMatrix}","page":"Home","text":"SingleLayer(equation::Laplace, source::AbstractManifold, # source manifold e.g. domain boundary, target::AbstractMatrix, # target points to compute operator, matrix_factory::Function=default_allocator)\n\nCompute the operator coefficients for source-target interaction\n\nArguments\n\nequation::Laplace: Partial Differential Equation corresponding to this operator\nsource::AbstractManifold: Manifold where the density is defined, i.e. boundary of the domain\ntarget::AbstractMatrix: Points where the potential is computed\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.SingleLayer"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.SingleLayer-Tuple{Laplace, BoundaryIntegralEquations.AbstractManifold, SingularCorrection}","page":"Home","text":"SingleLayer(equation::Laplace, source::AbstractManifold, correction::SingularCorrection, # order of kapur rokhlin singular correction, matrix_factory::Function=default_allocator)\n\nCompute the operator coefficients for source self interaction\n\nArguments\n\nequation::Laplace: Partial Differential Equation corresponding to this operator\nsource::AbstractManifold: Manifold where the density is defined and where the potential is computed, i.e. boundary of the domain\ncorrection::SingularCorrection: Approach to deal with the singularity\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.SingleLayer"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.ball-Tuple{Any, Any}","page":"Home","text":"ball(r, n)\n\nevenly distributed points in a circumference centered at the origin of radius r\n\nArguments\n\nr: radius of the circumference\nn: number of points\nreturn: matrix with datapoints\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.ball"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.cauchy_integral-Tuple{DiscreteClosedCurve, AbstractMatrix, AbstractVector}","page":"Home","text":"cauchy_integral(target, source::DiscreteClosedCurve, boundary_data)\n\ncomputes the inner value of a holomorphic function given its boundary data\n\nArguments\n\nsource::DiscreteClosedCurve: source manifold\ntarget: target points\nboundary_data: limit of the function at the curve\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.cauchy_integral"},{"category":"function","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.evaluate","page":"Home","text":"evaluate(problem::BoundaryValueProblem{Laplace,Dirichlet,Interior,<:DiscreteClosedCurve}, approach::Indirect, correction::HypersingularCorrection, φ::BoundaryDensity, target::AbstractMatrix, relative_cutoff=0.05, matrix_factory::Function=default_allocator)\n\nEvaluate the solution to a boundary value problem by using the solution to the associated boundary integral equation by the indirect approach.\n\nArguments\n\nproblem::BoundaryValueProblem{Laplace,Dirichlet,Interior,<:DiscreteClosedCurve}: problem whose solution is to be evaluated\napproach::Indirect: the indirect approach\ncorrection::HypersingularCorrection: type of correction to handle singular integral\nφ::BoundaryDensity: the solution to the associated boundary integral equation\ntarget::AbstractMatrix: points where the solution of the BVP needs evaluation\nrelative_cutoff: proportion of the characteristic length of the domain to switch between near-boundary evaluation using the Cauchy integral and conventional evaluation. Defaults to 5%.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.evaluate"},{"category":"function","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.evaluate-2","page":"Home","text":"evaluate(problem::BoundaryValueProblem{Laplace,Dirichlet,Interior,<:DiscreteClosedCurve}, approach::Indirect, correction::HypersingularCorrection, φ::BoundaryDensity, target::AbstractMatrix, relative_cutoff=0.05, matrix_factory::Function=default_allocator)\n\ncompute Hypersingular integral operator and call evaluate\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.evaluate"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.evaluate-Tuple{BoundaryValueProblem{Laplace, Dirichlet, Interior, <:DiscreteClosedCurve}, Direct, Neumann, AbstractMatrix}","page":"Home","text":"evaluate(problem::BoundaryValueProblem{Laplace,Dirichlet,Interior,<:DiscreteClosedCurve}, approach::Direct, τ::Neumann, target::AbstractMatrix, ;, matrix_factory::Function=default_allocator)\n\nevaluate the solution of a boundary value problem at requested locations, given the solution to the associated boundary integral equation through the direct approach, computing the required operators\n\nArguments\n\nproblem::BoundaryValueProblem{Laplace,Dirichlet,Interior,<:DiscreteClosedCurve}: boundary value problem to solve\napproach::Direct: approach to solve the boundary integral equation\nτ::Neumann: solution to the associated boundary integral equation\ntarget::AbstractMatrix: locations to evaluate the solution to the BVP\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.evaluate"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.evaluate-Tuple{BoundaryValueProblem{Laplace, Dirichlet, Interior, <:DiscreteClosedCurve}, Direct, Neumann, SingleLayer, DoubleLayer}","page":"Home","text":"evaluate(problem::BoundaryValueProblem{Laplace,Dirichlet,Interior,<:DiscreteClosedCurve}, ::Direct, τ::Neumann, S_target::SingleLayer, D_target::DoubleLayer)\n\nevaluate the solution of a boundary value problem at requested locations, given the solution to the associated boundary integral equation through the direct approach, and given precomputed operators\n\nArguments\n\nproblem::BoundaryValueProblem{Laplace,Dirichlet,Interior,<:DiscreteClosedCurve}: boundary value problem to solve\nτ::Neumann: solution to the boundary integral equation through the direct approach\nS_target::SingleLayer: source-target interaction integral operator\nD_target::DoubleLayer: source-target interaction integral operator\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.evaluate"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.holomorphism_boundary_limit-Tuple{BoundaryValueProblem{Laplace, Dirichlet, Interior, <:DiscreteClosedCurve}, BoundaryDensity}","page":"Home","text":"holomorphism_boundary_limit(problem<:BoundaryValueProblem{Laplace, Dirichlet, Interior}, density::BoundaryDensity)\n\ncomputes the interior limit v^-(x) x in Gamma of the holomorphic function v(x) x in mathbb C setminus Gamma, from the boundary density varphi which is the solution to the boundary integral equation by the indirect approach.\n\nThe The real part of v is the the double-layer potential of the boundary density, i.e., it is the solution to the Dirichlet laplace problem.\n\nThis means, if varphi is the solution to\n\n(D - frac12)varphi = sigma\n\n\nthen the solution to the interior Laplace problem with Dirichlet data sigma is\n\nu(x) = Re(v) = Dvarphi(x)\n\nand since v is holomorphic, it can be computed by a Cauchy integral, given the boundary limit of v.\n\nv(x) = frac12pi i int_Gammafracv^-(y)y - x dy\n\nThis function  computes the boundary limit v^-(x) from the boundary density varphi as:\n\nv^-(x) = - frac12 varphi(x) - frac12pi i textpv int_Gammafracvarphi(y)y-xdy\n\n\nArguments\n\nproblem::BoundaryValueProblem{Laplace, Dirichlet, Interior, <:DiscreteClosedCurve}: Boundary value problem to solve\ndensity::BoundaryDensity: Density that is the solution to the boundary integral equation associated to problem\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.holomorphism_boundary_limit"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.holomorphism_boundary_limit-Tuple{Exterior, DoubleLayer{Laplace}, BoundaryCondition, DiscreteClosedCurve}","page":"Home","text":"compute_boundary_limit(::Interior, op::SingleLayer{Laplace}, bc::BoundaryCondition, source::DiscreteClosedCurve)\n\n[TODO:description]\n\nArguments\n\nop::SingleLayer{Laplace}: [TODO:description]\nbc::BoundaryCondition: [TODO:description]\nsource::DiscreteClosedCurve: [TODO:description]\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.holomorphism_boundary_limit"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.kernel-Tuple{AdjointDoubleLayer{Laplace}, Any, Any}","page":"Home","text":"kernel(::AdjointDoubleLayer{Laplace}, r_norm_sq, r_dot_nx)\n\nCompute the kernel of the adjoint of the Laplace double-layer potential (DLP) integral operator, which is the normal derivative at x of the laplace SLP kernel.\n\nfracpartialpartial n_xk_textLap(x y) = nabla_x k_textLap(x y) cdot n_x = -frac12pi frac(x - y) cdot n_xx - y^2\n\nArguments\n\nr_norm_sq: square magnitude of the displacement vector\nr_dot_nx: dot product between the displacement vector and the normal vector at x\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.kernel"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.kernel-Tuple{DoubleLayer{Laplace}, Any, Any}","page":"Home","text":"kernel(::DoubleLayer{Laplace}, r_norm_sq, r_dot_ny)\n\nCompute the kernel of the Laplace double-layer potential integral operator, which is the normal derivative at y of the laplace SLP kernel.\n\nfracpartialpartial n_yk_textLap(x y) = nabla_y k_textLap(x y) cdot n_y= frac12pi frac(x - y) cdot n_yx - y^2\n\nArguments\n\nr_norm_sq: square magnitude of the displacement vector\nr_dot_ny: dot product between the displacement vector and the normal vector at y\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.kernel"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.kernel-Tuple{Hypersingular{Laplace}, Vararg{Any, 4}}","page":"Home","text":"kernel(::Hypersingular{Laplace}, r_norm_sq, r_dot_nx, r_dot_ny, nx_dot_ny)\n\nCompute the kernel of the Laplace hypersingular integral operator, which is the mixed second-order normal derivative of the laplace SLP kernel.\n\nfracpartial^2partial n_x partial n_yk_textLap(x y) = frac12pi left(frac-2((x - y) cdot n_x) ((x - y) cdot n_y)x - y^4 + fracn_x cdot n_yx - y^2right)\n\nArguments\n\nr_norm_sq: square magnitude of the displacement vector\nr_dot_nx: dot product between the displacement vector and the normal vector at x\nr_dot_ny: dot product between the displacement vector and the normal vector at y\nnx_dot_ny: dot product between the normal vectory at x and the normal vector at y\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.kernel"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.kernel-Tuple{SingleLayer{Laplace}, Any}","page":"Home","text":"kernel(::SingleLayer{Laplace}, r_norm_sq)\n\nCompute the kernel of the Laplace single-layer potential (SLP) integral operator\n\nk_textLap(x y) = -frac12pi logx - y\n\nArguments\n\nr_norm_sq: square magnitude of the displacement vector\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.kernel"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.matrix-Tuple{IntegralOperator}","page":"Home","text":"matrix(op::IntegralOperator)\n\nretrieve the matrix representation\n\nArguments\n\nop::IntegralOperator: operator\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.matrix"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.periodic_spectral_diff-Tuple{Any}","page":"Home","text":"periodic_spectral_diff(d)\n\nperiodic spectral derivative\n\nArguments\n\nf: matrix containing datapoints along curve\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.periodic_spectral_diff"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.populate_matrices!-Tuple{DiscreteClosedCurve, Vararg{IntegralOperator}}","page":"Home","text":"populate_matrices!(source::DiscreteClosedCurve{<:Real}, ops::IntegralOperator..., # variadic)\n\nCompute the coefficients of several requested self-interaction integral operators\n\nArguments\n\nsource::DiscreteClosedCurve{<:Real}: Manifold where the density is defined\n`ops::IntegralOperator... : List of operators that are required\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.populate_matrices!"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.populate_matrices!-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{DiscreteClosedCurve{T, TX, TV, TA, TS, TT, TN, TK, TW, CW} where {TX<:(AbstractMatrix{<:T}), TV<:(AbstractMatrix{<:T}), TA<:(AbstractMatrix{<:T}), TS<:(AbstractVector{<:T}), TT<:(AbstractMatrix{<:T}), TN<:(AbstractMatrix{<:T}), TK<:(AbstractVector{<:T}), TW<:(AbstractVector{<:T}), CW<:(AbstractVector{<:Complex{T}})}, AbstractMatrix{T}, Vararg{IntegralOperator}}} where T<:AbstractFloat","page":"Home","text":"populate_matrices!(source::DiscreteClosedCurve{<:Real}, ops, # tuple of operators with already allocated matrices)\n\nCompute the coefficients of several requested source-target interaction integral operators\n\nArguments\n\nsource::DiscreteClosedCurve{<:Real}: Manifold where the density is defined\n`ops::IntegralOperator... : List of operators that are required\ntarget_normals: Outward unitary normal vectors at the target locations, in case the AdjointDoubleLayer operator is requested\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.populate_matrices!"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.solve-Tuple{BoundaryValueProblem{Laplace, Dirichlet, Interior, <:DiscreteClosedCurve}, Direct, AdjointDoubleLayer, Hypersingular}","page":"Home","text":"solve(problem::BoundaryValueProblem{Laplace,Dirichlet,Interior,<:DiscreteClosedCurve}, ::Direct, D_star::AdjointDoubleLayer, H::Hypersingular)\n\nsolve the boundary integral equation associated to the given boundary value problem using tthe direct approach by internally computing the required integral operators  given precomputed integral operators\n\nArguments\n\nproblem::BoundaryValueProblem{Laplace,Dirichlet,Interior,<:DiscreteClosedCurve}: Boundary value problem to solve\nD_star::AdjointDoubleLayer: Precomputed D^* operator\nH::Hypersingular: Precomputed H operator\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.solve"},{"category":"method","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.solve-Tuple{BoundaryValueProblem{Laplace, Dirichlet, Interior, <:DiscreteClosedCurve}, Direct, HypersingularCorrection}","page":"Home","text":"solve(problem::BoundaryValueProblem{Laplace,Dirichlet,Interior,<:DiscreteClosedCurve}, approach::Direct, correction::HypersingularCorrection, ;, matrix_factory::Function=default_allocator)\n\nsolve the boundary integral equation associated to the given boundary value problem using tthe direct approach by internally computing the required integral operators\n\nArguments\n\nproblem::BoundaryValueProblem{Laplace,Dirichlet,Interior,<:DiscreteClosedCurve}: Problem to solve\napproach::Direct: Solution approach\ncorrection::HypersingularCorrection: Type of correction to use to deal with the singularity when computing the Hypersingular operator.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.solve"},{"category":"function","location":"#BoundaryIntegralEquations.starfish","page":"Home","text":"starfish(t, R=1, a=0.3, w=5)\n\nstarfish domain boundary in 2D as used by ref\n\nparametrization of a Jordan curve that is a domain boundary\n\nt |–> (x, y)\n\nArguments\n\nt: [TODO:parameter]\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"BoundaryIntegralEquations.starfish"}]
